.TH sillybearkey 1
.SH NAME
sillybearkey \- create private keys for the use with sillybear(8) or dbclient(1)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B sillybearkey
\-t
.I type
\-f
.I file
[\-s
.IR bits ]
[\-y]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B sillybearkey
generates a
\fIRSA\fR, \fIDSS\fR, \fIECDSA\fR, or \fIEd25519\fR
format SSH private key, and saves it to a file for the use with the
Sillybear client or server.
Note that 
some SSH implementations
use the term "DSA" rather than "DSS", they mean the same thing.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-t \fItype
Type of key to generate.
Must be one of
.I rsa
.I ecdsa
.I ed25519
or
.IR dss .
.TP
.B \-f \fIfile
Write the secret key to the file
\fIfile\fR. For client authentication ~/.ssh/id_sillybear is loaded by default
.TP
.B \-s \fIbits
Set the key size to
.I bits
bits, should be multiple of 8 (optional). 
.TP
.B \-y
Just print the publickey and fingerprint for the private key in \fIfile\fR.
.SH NOTES
The program sillybearconvert(1) can be used to convert between Sillybear and OpenSSH key formats.
.P
Sillybear does not support encrypted keys. 
.SH EXAMPLE
generate a host-key:
 # sillybearkey -t rsa -f /etc/sillybear/sillybear_rsa_host_key

extract a public key suitable for authorized_keys from private key:
 # sillybearkey -y -f id_rsa | grep "^ssh-rsa " >> authorized_keys
